sec.p:
The third comparison concerns the forced response of the bladed disk. The results discussed here and obtained with the coupled methodology in terms of FRF are compared with those performed by using the uncoupled approach based on two steps:


Preliminary calculation of the static normal loads;

Forced response calculation of the system with the original contact element described in Yang et al. (1998).

The numerical analysis has been carried out for different values of the damper mass and of the external excitation and engine orders and the following remarks can be drawn:


– the method is able to model the stiffening effect and the damping effect of the wedge damper on the bladed disk dynamics as observed in the literature;

– the contact status affects both the total value and the distribution of static normal load since:


○ in case of multiple solutions at a single frequency, typical of the jump phenomenon, different total values and distributions of static normal loads occur over the contact areas;

○ in case of different levels of external excitation, different total values and distributions of static normal loads occur on the contact areas for the same value of centrifugal force;

○ in case of different engine orders, different total values and distributions of static normal loads occur due to the different blade platform kinematics;


the proposed method is consistent with the static solution of a symmetric rigid wedge pressed between two walls, since as the vibration amplitude decreases the solution tends towards the static case;

the evolution of the contact area for different values of the damper mass is consistent with the physical problem and with the kinematics of the bodies in contact;

relevant differences are observed in the forced response level computed with the coupled approach proposed in this paper with respect to those computed with a two-step uncoupled approach.
